<paragraph id="AE8A66648B43F8C718284C329545D697" pageId="127" pageNumber="128">
<taxonomicName id="807F63BA2CEE01807C4DCD791B0EB33D" authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="C. E. Schnell ex Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="C. E. Schnell ex Kriebel" baseAuthorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia lancifolia" order="Myrtales" pageId="127" pageNumber="128" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="lancifolia" status="comb. et stat. nov.">Conostegia lancifolia</taxonomicName>
(Markgraf) C.E. Schnell ex Kriebel. Basionym: 
<taxonomicName id="C5C762EA5330254C3BCA78D27DB1DFE1" authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia centronioides subsp. var. var. lancifolia" order="Myrtales" pageId="127" pageNumber="128" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="variety" species="centronioides" status="comb. et stat. nov." subSpecies="var." variety="lancifolia">Conostegia centronioides var. lancifolia</taxonomicName>
Markgraf, Notizbl. Bot. Gart. Berlin-Dahlem 15: 377. 1941. Type: Ecuador. Mera: 1000 m, 8 November 1938, H. Schultze-Rhonhof 2966 (B, destroyed). Neotype designated here: Ecuador. Pastaza: between Mera and Moravia, 1000 m, 16 December 1955, E. Asplund 18868 (holoneotype: NY!).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A063BFB1067BB5B0B9D679A87E786691" pageId="127" pageNumber="128" type="description">
<paragraph id="6B42BDD9AB0E42EF257F520FF86713A8" pageId="127" pageNumber="128">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A94B5D5BECDEFAF821D08F7ED7ACCC8A" pageId="127" pageNumber="128">
Shrubs or small trees 1-5 m tall with tetragonal to rounded stems which are covered predominantly by stipitate stellate trichomes; nodal line present, somtimes obscured by indument. Leaves at a node equal to unequal in size. Petiole 0.4-1.8 cm. Leaf blades 5-17 
<normalizedToken id="52529AA98DCA2A95518E14157BD967FF" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2-6 cm, 3-5 slightly plinerved, elliptic to lanceolate, rounded to subacute at the base, the apex and acuminate, margins entire to undulate-denticulate, glabrous adaxially, pubescent mainly on the primary veins abaxially with indument like that of the stems. Inflorescence a terminal panicle 4-9 cm long branched above the base but sometimes appearing branched at the base because of multiple inflorescences arising at opposing meristems at the terminal node, accessory branches absent or present. Bracts and bracteoles 1.5-3 mm long, linear. Pedicels 1-3 mm long. Flowers 7-9 merous, calyptrate. Floral buds 6-9.5 
<normalizedToken id="40C5450D578E30AD3ADB94FFC82B845C" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
3-6.5 mm, ovoid to obovoid, slightly constricted below the calyptra, the hypanthium and calyptra undifferentiated; hypanthium 3-3.5 
<normalizedToken id="ED0D3739AB357B66517AE136C7968A0A" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
3.75-4.25 mm, pubescent with sessile and/or stipitate stellate trichomes. Petals 8-10 
<normalizedToken id="9773E1C9978A72D4CBCBEBDA69797918" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5-6 mm, white, obtriangular, posture not seen, glabrous on both surfaces, emarginate apically. Stamens 30-42, 7-8 mm long, the filament 4-4.5 mm, apparently white, anthers 3-3.5 
<normalizedToken id="D2EFB676C25B37466FB8DEEAFAAD149D" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.5-0.75 mm, linear subulate, pale yellow (in rehydrated specimen), the pore ca. 0.18 mm, terminal to slightly ventrally inclined. Ovary 11-12-locular, inferior, glabrous and forming a collar around the style base; style ca. 7.5-8 mm, gently bending from the base, glabrous, the style appears to be exserted but difficult to assess in the rehydrated material as well as if it is bent opposite the stamens or not, stigma capitate, ca. 2 mm wide. Mature berry not seen.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B7EA2D47BF94C5E145615DD15BA5E0F4" pageId="128" pageNumber="129" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="2E458F4DF737CBBE1CF1E96911C0F66C" pageId="128" pageNumber="129">
<pageBreakToken id="56C09ED8B9B12F790C5AD21C98FE476E" pageId="128" pageNumber="129" start="start">Distribution</pageBreakToken>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9D726AB3592725887C611AA5FCFF5946" pageId="128" pageNumber="129">
(Fig. 
<figureCitation id="AF56580687286366DA1ECE0F56C3D901" captionStart="Figure 122" captionStartId="F122" captionText="Figure 122. Distribution of Conostegia lancifolia." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.67.6703.figure122" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/96480" pageId="128" pageNumber="129">122</figureCitation>
). Southeastern foothills of the Andes in Ecuador at 800-1200 m in elevation.
</paragraph>
<caption id="08B776680B55F5511976B5F0AC0047EF" ID-Zenodo-Dep="973889" doi="10.3897/phytokeys.67.6703.figure122" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/96480" pageId="128" pageNumber="129" start="Figure 122" startId="F122">
<paragraph id="0A18D4B40EF2E5D2F51B97BC43782545" pageId="128" pageNumber="129">
<emphasis id="0D6D42CCDAF22165DB9E02164A09C7CA" bold="true" pageId="128" pageNumber="129">Figure 122.</emphasis>
Distribution of 
<taxonomicName id="A85D81D7D5BD43836CE5B178AA525E90" authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="C. E. Schnell ex Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="C. E. Schnell ex Kriebel" baseAuthorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia lancifolia" order="Myrtales" pageId="128" pageNumber="129" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="lancifolia">
<emphasis id="459024CCEBD8A47AEB72451551DEC7CB" italics="true" pageId="128" pageNumber="129">Conostegia lancifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="1F1AB2AE56BD58A87389256021981F5E" pageId="128" pageNumber="129">
<bibRefCitation id="89381C52944FF2AAA89F20F8381C4428" author="Schnell, CE" journalOrPublisher="Harvard University" pageId="243" pageNumber="244" refId="B77" refString="Schnell, CE, 1996. The Genus Conostegia (Melastomataceae). Harvard University" title="The Genus Conostegia (Melastomataceae)" year="1996">Schnell (1996)</bibRefCitation>
noted that as like for 
<taxonomicName id="49F787A6E26010C755BAFD591A77BFD2" authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia centronoides" order="Myrtales" pageId="128" pageNumber="129" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="centronoides">
<emphasis id="7BFDC6487BBDC5804EA715F41E0DD5FF" italics="true" pageId="128" pageNumber="129">Conostegia centronoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the holotype of 
<taxonomicName id="A07276DC83650BD1875F9F76B4A46D2E" authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia centronoides subsp. var. var. lancifolia" order="Myrtales" pageId="128" pageNumber="129" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="variety" species="centronoides" subSpecies="var." variety="lancifolia">Conostegia centronoides var. lancifolia</taxonomicName>
was lost during the war in Berlin. I concur with 
<bibRefCitation id="186FE9622C9A33EAA81CF81822080084" author="Schnell, CE" journalOrPublisher="Harvard University" pageId="243" pageNumber="244" refId="B77" refString="Schnell, CE, 1996. The Genus Conostegia (Melastomataceae). Harvard University" title="The Genus Conostegia (Melastomataceae)" year="1996">Schnell (1996)</bibRefCitation>
in that the description of the latter including stipitate stellate hairs and narrowly ovate leaves matches topotypical material which Schnell cited as the neotype (
<emphasis id="965952DBF187C37DA00F9DF1D86935B6" italics="true" pageId="128" pageNumber="129">E. Asplund 18868</emphasis>
). For this reason and because the work of 
<bibRefCitation id="B8A58B246327F4C0C573932787B600FA" author="Schnell, CE" journalOrPublisher="Harvard University" pageId="243" pageNumber="244" refId="B77" refString="Schnell, CE, 1996. The Genus Conostegia (Melastomataceae). Harvard University" title="The Genus Conostegia (Melastomataceae)" year="1996">Schnell (1996)</bibRefCitation>
wasa not published, the neotypification is made here. 
<bibRefCitation id="852AA0D62349CE38F0AA3A6C308DCED9" author="Schnell, CE" journalOrPublisher="Harvard University" pageId="243" pageNumber="244" refId="B77" refString="Schnell, CE, 1996. The Genus Conostegia (Melastomataceae). Harvard University" title="The Genus Conostegia (Melastomataceae)" year="1996">Schnell (1996)</bibRefCitation>
included in his circumscription of 
<taxonomicName id="2466240346D7DC34F4B425728E194F40" authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="C. E. Schnell ex Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="C. E. Schnell ex Kriebel" baseAuthorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia lancifolia" order="Myrtales" pageId="128" pageNumber="129" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="lancifolia">
<emphasis id="B21E6199D31B5AC8AAE2C5DB324C5C35" italics="true" pageId="128" pageNumber="129">Conostegia lancifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the decurrent leaved and large leaf blade plants here referred to as 
<taxonomicName id="3537BF4BF149FB66FFEFFB2BC28BA26F" authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia ortizae" order="Myrtales" pageId="128" pageNumber="129" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ortizae">
<emphasis id="AA8711D0E7BA4DE2516D7BAC3A97E15E" italics="true" pageId="128" pageNumber="129">Conostegia ortizae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Schnell pointed out that if intermediates between the two morphotypes did not arise they might as well be called subspecies or species. Considering they are easy to distinguish they are here proposed as different species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
